<tr>
<td>
<div class="content-box pad-box-micro border border-b border-t" style="background-color: whitesmoke;">
<h2 style="text-align: center;"><strong><a class="icon-syllabus" style="color: black; text-decoration: none;"> Syllabus</a></strong></h2>
</div>
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>
<p><strong> </strong><strong>Writing about Food </strong></p>
<p><em>Syllabus for Fall 2017</em></p>
<p> </p>
<p><em>Hybrid Course</em></p>
<p> </p>
<p><span style="font-size: 12pt;">Writing about Food Fall 2017 is a journalism-based class that will give you a framework for writing about all aspects of food, using a news reporting perspective. With so much changing in the world of food -- the explosion of farmers' markets, artisanal food makers, and the new ways in which we look at food through the lenses of environment, animal welfare, nutrition and home cooking -- stories are waiting to be told. The framework will help structure storytelling about the food in our world today. Students will find stories and issues, interview, report, and write as well as workshop other students' work.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-size: 12pt;">This hybrid course includes an intensive weekend in September 2017 that will outline the course plus give a solid basis for first projects, giving students a head start for the online portion of the course. In-class writing assignments, an in-class interview with a chef, a restaurant reviewer and others, as well as outside-the-class reporting will be included. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-size: 12pt;">For the online sessions, students will complete writing assignments plus assigned readings that show a range of food writing, along with tips, direction, and help in collecting information and shaping stories, conducting interviews, and restaurant reviewing tactics. We will also read and critique examples of published food writing, both current and classic. There will be plenty of interaction between each student and the teacher as well as interaction with other class members. The class will also include practical ways for students to approach editors, market their work, and find outlets for work.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-size: 12pt;">A Facebook Page will allow students to interact with links to articles, news, and food events. Instagram will also be used to share photos and food news.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-size: 12pt;"> </span></p>
<p><span style="font-size: 12pt;">Our textbooks will be "Best Food Writing of 2016" and "Will Write for Food" (third edition) Additionally, there will be links to articles from magazines, newspapers, and blogs. Short video clips will be used from time to time. Graduate students in journalism will have an additional project on a food issue, to be determined by the students and teacher.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-size: 12pt;">You will be expected to complete a total of three short in-class assignments during the intensive weekend. During the rest of the semester, there will be three major written assignments – a full profile of 1,000 to 1,200 words; a restaurant review of 800 words; and a recipe story of 600-800 words plus recipe. There will also be one to two smaller assignments of 300 words or less. Graduate student will also be required to write a 1,000-1,200-word issue piece. One assignment will be workshopped in class. Students will have opportunity to revise the three longer pieces, plus the issues piece for graduate students. Timely submission of written work is essential to this course, especially because of the online aspect. Productive and consistent participation in the intensive weekend and in the online classes is also very important.</span></p>
<p><em>WAF Week by Week</em></p>
<p><em>All written assignments are due by noon Tuesday before a class, ie Sept. 20 at noon for Sept 22 . This is for the sake of class discussion as well as making sure the online portion goes smoothly. Assignments will be posted on Canvas; the Syllabus with assignments outlined will also be on Canvas.</em></p>
<p><em> </em></p>
<p><strong>First Class Thursday, August 31</strong></p>
<p>INTRODUCTORY CLASS</p>
<p>Teacher introductions. Introduction to class materials. Discussion of requirements, how the Intensive Weekend and online classes will work.</p>
<p>Discussion of workshopping, how it is conducted and what to consider when workshopping.</p>
<p>Short writing exercise on what food writing means to you or a food memory -- no more than 200 words -- with discussion to follow. THIS MUST BE DONE IN CLASS AND SUBMITTED TO TEACHER BY END OF CLASS.</p>
<p><strong>Sept. 14:</strong></p>
<p><strong>Assignments</strong>: Be sure you have the assigned textbooks for class before this class and also for the Intensive Weekend<em>: Best Food Writing 2016 and Will Write for Food. </em></p>
<p><strong>Reading </strong><em>1. </em>Read and be prepared to discuss first chapter of <em>Will Write for Food: </em>“What, Exactly is Food Writing,” concentrating on describing food and taste through the senses</p>
<ol start="2">
<li>Read and be prepared to discuss “Filter Fish” from <em>Best Food Writing of 2016 </em>with concentration on voice of author.</li>
<li>Read and be prepared to discuss New Food Economy article on DeCoster eggs http://newfoodeconomy.com/egg-mogul-jack-decoster-sickened-56000-people-hell-do-just-three-months-in-prison/</li>
</ol>
<p><strong>Writing: </strong>Short (no more than 350 words) critiquing either 2 or 3 of readings: Does this work; what are questions you still have; does the lede draw you in. Submit to teacher on Canvas by Tuesday, Sept. 12. SLUG: YOUR LAST NAME/CRITIQUE 1</p>
<p><em>In Class: </em></p>
<p>Discuss reading assignments 1. Food description 2 Voice in Food Writing 3 Issues in Food Writing/investigative writing about food</p>
<p>Teacher will explain profile assignment with tips on how to find and contact subjects, how to interview, how to structure – class will discuss profile subjects</p>
<p>Discuss outlining and why it is important for longer assignments. </p>
<p>Discuss How to Pitch</p>
<p><strong>Assignments for Sept. 16-17 Intensive Weekend: Readings</strong> 1.<em>Will Write for Food </em>Chapter 2, “Gastronomical You.”</p>
<p>2.Read Alan Richman’ profile “At Lucali, Pizza for the A-List and the Landlady Upstairs” <a href="https://www.nytimes.com/2015/08/19/dining/pizza-lucali-mark-iacono-profile.html?mcubz">https://www.nytimes.com/2015/08/19/dining/pizza-lucali-mark-iacono-profile.html?mcubz</a></p>
<p> </p>
<p>3.Have Profile Subject (2-3) and be prepared to discuss/defend</p>
<p><strong>Writing assignment </strong>: (1) a short, no more 150 word pitch for a profile you might do; bring to Intensive Weekend for discussion</p>
<p><em> </em></p>
<p><em><span style="font-size: 14pt;"><strong>Intensive Weekend at Harvard</strong></span></em></p>
<p>Saturday, Sept. 16, 9 am-5 pm*</p>
<p>9-10 am <strong>Meet and Greet</strong></p>
<p>-- Teacher describes the next two days and how there will be a variety of experiences, writing opportunities, and foundations for later writing assignments</p>
<p>Journalistic concepts outlined and discussed as pertains to this class. Guidelines about fact-based Journalism as pertains to food writing: who, what, when, why and how; accurate quoting; a way of looking out at the world rather than self-reverential.</p>
<p>“It’s not about me”</p>
<p>--Class members interview each other with quotes, reporting.</p>
<p>The interviewer then introduces class member, utilizing reporting, quotes, and writing.</p>
<p>10-11:15 <strong>Senses and snack</strong></p>
<p>Describing food through the senses and how this is especially important in food journalism. Snacks are chosen. In-class writing assignment: Students write about why they picked sweet or savory and describe what they ate, using concrete terms ie from Pages 7-11 of “What Exactly is Food Writing” “Will Write for Food.”</p>
<p>11:15-12:30 Profile assignment and <span>Voice : How Alan Richman’s profile reveals his subject while subtly showing voice. How did he (or did not) bring this person alive. Is voice the same as opinion?</span></p>
<p>12:30-2 Roving reporters: Class is instructed to use their lunch break to interview someone in Harvard Square about food, take notes for in-class writing assignment.</p>
<p>Students go out to do interviews.</p>
<p>2-2:30 Very short discussion on man/woman on street interviews. Were you able to get usuable quotes. We'll write about these tomorrow (Sunday)</p>
<p>Restaurants, restaurant reviews and place in today's society</p>
<p>2:30-3:30 Tony Maws, owner of two Cambridge restaurants,<span>is introduced and speaks to class about restaurants, cooking, the business angles and creativity, and sustainability. Students take notes and ask questions. </span> This is one choice for later mini profile.</p>
<p> </p>
<p>3:30-4:30 Unfortunately, due to medical emergency Prof Weesner can't attend.  Teacher will discuss restaurant reviewing. Reviews will be distributed and discussed. Class discusses reviewing, its place in today’s Yelp world, the reviews, what a review should and shouldn’t be.</p>
<p><a href="http://www.nytimes.com/2012/11/14/dining/reviews/restaurant-review-guys-american-kitchen-bar-in-times-square.html?emc=eta1">http://www.nytimes.com/2012/11/14/dining/reviews/restaurant-review-guys-american-kitchen-bar-in-times-square.html?emc=eta1</a></p>
<p><a href="http://www.bostonglobe.com/lifestyle/food-dining/2017/06/20/where-would-julia-child-eat-think-here/inEN6snqktG9cfZNYQQCzM/story.html?s_campaign=8315">http://www.bostonglobe.com/lifestyle/food-dining/2017/06/20/where-would-julia-child-eat-think-here/inEN6snqktG9cfZNYQQCzM/story.html?s_campaign=8315</a></p>
<p><a href="http://www.latimes.com/food/jonathan-gold/la-fo-gold-rossoblu-review-20170619-story.html">http://www.latimes.com/food/jonathan-gold/la-fo-gold-rossoblu-review-20170619-story.html</a></p>
<p> </p>
<p><a href="https://www.eater.com/2014/3/7/6267309/chefs-and-restaurateurs-weigh-in-how-to-handle-yelp">https://www.eater.com/2014/3/7/6267309/chefs-and-restaurateurs-weigh-in-how-to-handle-yelp</a></p>
<p> </p>
<p> </p>
<p>4:30-5 Explanation of that night’s assignments: Reviewing wherever you eat. </p>
<p>Read Kim Severson's article on Ruth Reichl <a href="https://www.nytimes.com/2015/09/16/dining/ruth-reichl-my-kitchen-year.html?mcubz">https://www.nytimes.com/2015/09/16/dining/ruth-reichl-my-kitchen-year.html?mcubz</a> for discussion on Sunday</p>
<p> </p>
<p>SUNDAY, Sept 17, 9 am-5 pm*</p>
<p>9-10:45 Talk about your reviewing experiences.</p>
<p>Write in-class reviews of 200-450 words, read reviews and discuss</p>
<p>10:45-11:00 Short break if time</p>
<p>11-11:45 Issues food writing -- what is it, is it the future of food writing? How does issues reporting differ from Op ed? examples (Arnett in Edible Boston; addictive food in NYT) and discussion</p>
<p><a href="http://www.nytimes.com/2013/02/24/magazine/the-extraordinary-science-of-junk-food.html?emc=eta1">http://www.nytimes.com/2013/02/24/magazine/the-extraordinary-science-of-junk-food.html?emc=eta1</a></p>
<p><a href="http://www.edibleboston.com/blog/2017/6/7/new-garden-society">http://www.edibleboston.com/blog/2017/6/7/new-garden-society</a></p>
<p> </p>
<p>11:45-12:30 Class goes to Farmers Market, hears from farmer, asks questions for later assignment</p>
<p>12:30-1 lunch break</p>
<p>1-2:30 Food photography segment with photographer/videographer Ron Cowie, centering on blogging, techniques. photographing food</p>
<p>Twitter/Instagram and uses in Food Journalism today</p>
<p>2:30-3:30 Short in-class assignment on interviews in Harvard Square on Saturday.</p>
<p>Board: Outlining and why it is important. Also leads, nut grafs if not discussed earlier</p>
<p>3:30-3:45 short break</p>
<p>3:45-4:30 Discussions of 2nd chapter of Will Write for Food. PPt on  Severson on Ruth Reichl --Crisis points and tension <a href="https://www.nytimes.com/2015/09/16/dining/ruth-reichl-my-kitchen-year.html?mcubz=1">https://www.nytimes.com/2015/09/16/dining/ruth-reichl-my-kitchen-year.html?mcubz=1</a></p>
<p> </p>
<p>4:30-5:00  Talk to graduate students about issues piece</p>
<ul>
<li>Timing of speakers and sequences may shift slightly</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Sept. 21 </strong><em>OFFICE HOUR Sept. 21 for those who want to discuss profile project, or issues project for graduates. 5:30-6:30</em></p>
<p><strong>October 5</strong></p>
<p><strong>Assignments: Readings: </strong><em>Will Write for Food, </em>Chapter 3 "The Food Writer's Mise en Place"</p>
<p>Reading and critiquing first batch of profile drafts (Link to first profiles will be emailed to students by evening of Oct. 3, critique and be prepared to workshop in class Oct. 5)</p>
<p><strong>Writing assignment </strong></p>
<p>First Draft of Profile; due by noon, Oct. 3 SLUG YOUR LAST NAME/Profile 1st draft</p>
<p><strong><em>IN Class</em></strong></p>
<p>Discuss reading</p>
<p>Workshop first profiles: Students will read critiques of others’ works aloud; teacher will offer commentary</p>
<p>Teacher will give concrete ways to improve material and tips for editing, trimming, and polishing profiles</p>
<p>Discuss shaping final profile</p>
<p><strong>October 19</strong></p>
<p><strong>Assignments: Readings: </strong>“Waiting for the 8<sup>th</sup>” Eli Saslow, issues piece</p>
<p><a href="http://www.washingtonpost.com/sf/national/2013/12/15/waiting-for-the-8th/?utm_term=.98a99c877269">http://www.washingtonpost.com/sf/national/2013/12/15/waiting-for-the-8th/?utm_term=.98a99c877269</a></p>
<p>Read and bring to class 2 food stories that you like – can be business-related, issues, profiles – NOT RESTAURANT REVIEWS</p>
<p><strong>Writing: </strong></p>
<p>Read and critique last Profiles for Workshopping (Links will be emailed to class by Oct. 8</p>
<p>Write a mini profile from Intensive Weekend interviews SLUG: YOUR LAST NAME/MINI-PROFILE</p>
<p><em>In Class</em></p>
<p>Second week of Workshopping</p>
<p>Discuss reading and issues pieces – the human element in food, how to get deep into a subject</p>
<p>Students discuss stories they found – why they liked them, what the pieces revealed about the world or a person through food</p>
<p>Discuss restaurant reviews and how to select a restaurant to review.</p>
<p><strong>November 2</strong></p>
<p><strong>Assignments: Readings: </strong>Ruth Reichl’s famous review of Le Cirque ; “Dinner and Deception,” by Edward Frame, <em>Best Food Writing of 2016</em></p>
<p><strong>Writing: </strong></p>
<p>Bring to class example of a restaurant review; write a short paragraph to discuss in class why the review worked or didn’t work</p>
<p>Polish your profile and be ready to discuss questions, concerns in class</p>
<p><em>In Class</em></p>
<p>Schlesinger Collection at Radcliffe (MFK Fisher, Julia Child etc papers and cookbook collection) A director will talk about collection and how to access it.</p>
<p>Discuss published restaurant reviews</p>
<p>Discuss current state of reviewing, Yelp, etc</p>
<p>Discuss comic/ironic element in reading and in restaurant/food writing – what is funny, what works, what doesn’t. Discuss Le Cirque review and Frame’s piece</p>
<p>Student will tell class what restaurant they’re reviewing and why.</p>
<p>Discussion of Recipe with Story assignment</p>
<p><strong>November 16</strong></p>
<p><strong>Assignments: Readings </strong>Melissa Clark stories with recipes (2) will be emailed to class by Nov. 8, “Sorry, Blue Apron, the Joys of Cooking Can’t Fit into a Box” Corby Kummer, <em>Best Food Stories 2016; </em>read Peruvian potato travel piece <a href="http://www.saveur.com/peru-potatoes">http://www.saveur.com/peru-potatoes</a></p>
<p><strong>Writing assignments</strong>: First draft of restaurant review SLUG: YOUR LAST NAME/RESTAURANT REVIEW 1st Draft</p>
<p><strong>Final of profile due Nov. 20 SLUG: Last name/Profile final</strong></p>
<p><em>In Class</em></p>
<p>Discuss recipe stories.</p>
<p>Discuss pitches for recipe stories – how to do them, where to direct them, what works what doesn’t, why doing a pitch is a good idea to define/sharpen your writing</p>
<p>Discuss travel pieces and the journalistic emphasis on people in travel/food stories</p>
<p>Discuss last points on final drafts of profile pieces; marketplace ideas on profiles – where would you sell them, what kind of audience would be interested</p>
<p>Discuss restaurant reviews and any issues/problems</p>
<p><strong>November 30</strong></p>
<p><strong>Assignments: Readings: </strong>Find and read a classic piece of food writing – some examples are James Beard, Julia Child, MFK Fisher, Edna Lewis, Waverly Root, AJ Liebling, Clementine Paddleford, Colette, Ernest Hemingway, RJ Apple – Be prepared to read and discuss in class</p>
<p><strong> Writing assignment </strong>Final draft of restaurant review SLUG: Last name/Restaurant Review Final</p>
<p>Pitch to an editor on Recipe story with recipe description SLUG: YOUR LAST NAME/RECIPE PITCH</p>
<p><strong>FOR GRADUATE STUDENTS: First draft of issue piece of 1,200 words or less as discussed with teacher SLUG: YOUR LAST NAME/ISSUES</strong></p>
<p><em>In Class</em></p>
<p>Be prepared to discuss your restaurant review; all students should have short comments, each will read lead: Does the lead work, does the review either make you want to go there and/or is useful to the reader</p>
<p>Discuss and read classic food writing in class: Why it’s important to read the classics, how food writing has changed for the better, not for the better? Voice in classical food writing</p>
<p><strong>December 14</strong></p>
<p><strong>Assignments: Reading: </strong>Find a published example of food writing with a strong voice to share with class. It could be something you really like or really hate. Or it could be great but flawed in some definable way. Write a short (no more than 200 words) defense of your ideas for discussion in class.</p>
<p>Find 1-3 examples of blogs and/or tweets by established food writers</p>
<p><strong>Writing assignment: </strong>Recipe story with recipe</p>
<p>Graph on piece you chose for strong voice in food writing (See above)</p>
<p>Graduate students: Finished issues pieces (due Dec. 21)</p>
<p><em>In Class</em></p>
<p>Students will read part or all of recipe piece lede, class will discuss</p>
<p>The Marketplace: discussion by teacher with extensive interviews/clips from working freelancers and editors.</p>
<p>Discussion of published food writing with a voice</p>
<p>Blogging and Twitter: Place in food journalism today</p>
<p>Course wrap-up: Highlights from writings on what we learned and what we wished we know more about</p>
<p><strong>Finished recipe stories are due Dec. 18</strong></p>
<p><strong>Finished graduate issue pieces are due Dec 21 Slug: Last name/Issues Final</strong></p>
<p><strong> </strong></p>
<p><strong>Deadlines</strong></p>
<p>First Draft Full Profile Oct. 3</p>
<p>Mini Profile from Intensive Weekend interviews, Oct. 19</p>
<p>Final Full Profile Nov. 20</p>
<p>First Draft Restaurant Review Nov. 16</p>
<p>Final Restaurant Review Nov. 30</p>
<p>First Draft Recipe Story Dec. 14</p>
<p>Final Draft Recipe Story Dec. 18-20</p>
<p>Graduate Issues Piece First Draft Nov. 30</p>
<p>Final Graduate Issues Piece Dec. 21</p>
<p> </p>
<p><strong>Grading will be on following criteria:</strong></p>
<p><strong>For Undergraduates</strong></p>
<p>Mini-profile – 10 percent</p>
<p>Profile - 40 percent</p>
<p>Review - 25 percent</p>
<p>Recipe story - 25 percent</p>
<p><strong>For Graduate Students</strong></p>
<p>Mini profile 5 percent</p>
<p>Profile 30 percent</p>
<p>Review 20</p>
<p>Recipe story 20</p>
<p>Issues piece 25</p>
<p> </p>
<p><strong>PLEASE NOTE THESE HARVARD EXTENSION POLICIES</strong></p>
<h2>PLAGIARISM</h2>
<p>Plagiarism is the theft of someone else’s ideas and work. It is the incorporation of facts, ideas, or specific language that are not common knowledge, are taken from another source, and are not properly cited.</p>
<p>Whether a student copies verbatim or simply rephrases the ideas of another without properly acknowledging the source, the theft is the same. A computer program written as part of the student’s academic work is, like a paper, expected to be the student’s original work and subject to the same standards of representation. In the preparation of work submitted to meet course, program, or school requirements, whether a draft or a final version of a paper, project, take-home exam, computer program, placement exam, application essay, oral presentation, or other work, students must take great care to distinguish their own ideas and language from information derived from sources. Sources include published and unpublished primary and secondary materials, the Internet, and information and opinions of other people.</p>
<p>Extension School students are responsible for following the standards of proper citation to avoid plagiarism. A useful resource is<span> </span><a href="http://usingsources.fas.harvard.edu/icb/icb.do"><em>The Harvard Guide to Using Sources</em></a><span> </span>prepared by the<a href="http://writingprogram.fas.harvard.edu/">Harvard College Writing Program</a><span> </span>and the Extension School’s<span> </span><a href="https://www.extension.harvard.edu/node/17051">tips to avoid plagiarism</a>.</p>
<p> </p>
<h2>RESEARCH, FABRICATION, AND FALSIFICATION</h2>
<p>Students are expected to be honest and accurate in all work submitted, whether it involves scientific research or writing articles in journalism courses, or any other course. Fabrication is the intentional act of making up data, results, or quotes, and includes falsely citing sources or citing sources never utilized.  Falsification is the manipulation of research including the distortion or omission of important data or results. Like plagiarism, fabrication and falsification are serious violations of academic integrity that are subject to review by the Administrative Board for disciplinary action.  </p>
<p>The University deeply values the integrity of science with sound and safe research practices by students and faculty. Individually and collectively, student and faculty researchers are expected to safeguard and maintain the University’s policies and practices with respect to scientific misconduct. All researchers are reminded that sponsoring agencies also have such concerns, and that the University must inform the sponsors of any serious transgressions of their policies, as well as of any investigations related to sponsored research. Sponsors may take action independent of the University.  </p>
<p>Exclusion from a Course</p>
<p>A student who is consistently not prepared for class, fails to attend class or participate online, and whose gross neglect of work is disruptive to the progress of instruction may, after written warning by the instructor, be excluded from the course. If it is before the withdrawal deadline the student may voluntarily withdraw from the course for a WD or WN grade as an alternative to exclusion, but may no longer attend or participate. A student who is excluded from a course is prohibited from continuing with it in any way, including attending classes, participating online, taking exams, and submitting work. The student is assigned the permanent notation EXD (excluded from course), which is equivalent to a failing grade and earns no credit for the course. A student who is excluded from a course is not eligible for a tuition refund for that course. </p>
</td>
</tr>
